					<head>Jewish liturgy</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/n80040114" rend="visible">
						<summary>A maḥzor containing the services for the special Sabbaths, Pesaḥ and Shavu῾ot, according to the German rite.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/n80040114">
							<locus from="1r" to="195v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Maḥzor </title>
							<title xml:lang="he">מחזור</title>
							<note>
								<p>The inner side of the flyleaf at the beginning (folio 1) contains an inadequate description of the manuscript in Latin.</p>
							</note>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="2v" to="56r"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Services for the special Sabbaths</title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="56r" to="134v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Services for Pesaḥ </title>
							</msItem>
							<msItem rend="v">
								<locus from="134v" to="195v"/>
								<title xml:lang="en">Services for Shavu῾ot</title>
							</msItem>
							<filiation>Cf. the contents of Add. 10456 (<ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">659</ref>) and Add. 18967 (<ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">660</ref>) part 3.</filiation>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of approximately 14th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<extent>195 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>365</height>
										<width>265</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>220</height>
										<width>160</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>195 folios (+ 2 modern paper flyleaves at the beginning and at the end). Folio 1 is a paper flyleaf.</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Quires of mostly 8 leaves each, signed with catchwords at the end.</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Defective at the end.</p>
									<p>Folio 112 partly mutilated.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1" ruledLines="20" writtenLines="20">
									<p>Uniform layout. Last line written within the ruling.</p>
									<p>Pricking and ruling is visible. </p>
									<p>Hair-side and flesh-side of the folios are hardly distinguishable.
</p>
									<p>Initial words given in much larger bold square characters.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="1">
							<summary>Ashkenazi square script of the 14th century. Punctuated.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="sole"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>A Latin description of the manuscript has been pasted on folio <locus n="1v"/>.</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p> 	Post-1600. Harleian thick red leather binding with gold-tooling.</p>
								<p>Spine: 'Pars T. Machazor Judaeorum Germanorum. Hebr. Cod. Sec. XIV. Mus. Brit. Bibl. Harl. 5714. Plut. XXXIII.I.'</p>
								<p>Boxed.</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
					</physDesc>
					<history rend="visible">
						<origin notBefore="1300" notAfter="1399"/>
						<provenance>
							<p>
								<name type="place">Germany</name>
							</p>
						</provenance>
						<acquisition>
							<p>The Harley Collection, formed by <name type="person" role="owner">Robert Harley</name> (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and <name type="person" role="owner">Edward Harley</name> (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts, inscribed as usual by their librarian, <name type="person">Humfrey Wanley</name>, '18 die Januarij, A.D. 1723/4' (folio <locus n="2r"/>). Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, <name type="person" role="owner">Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles</name> (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, <name type="person" role="owner">Margaret Cavendish Bentinck</name> (b. 1715, d.1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in <date calendar="Gregorian">1753 </date>to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.</p>
							<date>1753</date>
						</acquisition>
					</history>
